00:30:48,300 --> 00:30:53,300
But I'm going to say it this way, what does calculus want, and how does it get what it wants?

360
00:30:53,300 --> 00:30:58,300
So the answer to what it wants, before I tell you what calculus really is,

361
00:30:59,300 --> 00:31:03,300
what calculus wants to do is make hard problems simpler.

362
00:31:03,300 --> 00:31:08,300
And this came as a surprise to my editor, who did not know any math when I was writing this book,

363
00:31:08,300 --> 00:31:13,300
but he eventually said to me, I now get it after reading three drafts of the book, I get,

364
00:31:13,300 --> 00:31:17,300
no, I mean he kept telling me do this, do that, I kept changing it, but by the third one he said,

365
00:31:17,300 --> 00:31:19,300
I'm really starting to get what this is.

366
00:31:19,300 --> 00:31:25,300
The books are so fat, the calculus textbooks are so big, because the problems are so hard,

367
00:31:25,300 --> 00:31:31,300
but somehow you have found a way, not you, me, but I mean the people that do calculus

368
00:31:31,300 --> 00:31:35,300
have found a way to make very hard problems tractable.

369
00:31:35,300 --> 00:31:37,300
Now, how do they do it?

370
00:31:37,300 --> 00:31:40,300
Okay, so how does calculus get what it wants?

371
00:31:40,300 --> 00:31:46,300
Here's the strategy, it's going to slice hard problems into smaller pieces.

372
00:31:46,300 --> 00:31:48,300
Okay, that might sound familiar.

373
00:31:48,300 --> 00:31:51,300
You know that every good problem solver says if a problem is too hard,

374
00:31:51,300 --> 00:31:55,300
break it down and solve simpler, easier problems first.

375
00:31:55,300 --> 00:31:57,300
Fine, that's a time-honored strategy.

376
00:31:57,300 --> 00:32:05,300
But calculus is a maniacal strategy that keeps doing this forever, indefinitely odd infinitum.

377
00:32:05,300 --> 00:32:09,300
So calculus takes this idea of chopping to the infinite limit.

378
00:32:09,300 --> 00:32:18,300
It keeps cutting and cutting and cutting and never stops until what's left is an infinite number of infinitesimal pieces.

379
00:32:18,300 --> 00:32:23,300
This is the big idea at the heart of calculus, I'm going to call it the infinity principle,

380
00:32:23,300 --> 00:32:31,300
which is that if you cut a problem of a certain class of math or physics problems,

381
00:32:31,300 --> 00:32:35,300
and actually many problems nowadays, even in biology or the social sciences,

382
00:32:35,300 --> 00:32:41,300
if you can subdivide it into infinitely many infinitesimal pieces, you have a strategy,

383
00:32:41,300 --> 00:32:46,300
which is you're going to solve the problem first for the tiny pieces, and that tends to be easy.

384
00:32:46,300 --> 00:32:49,300
Much easier than the problem originally was.

385
00:32:49,300 --> 00:32:51,300
So that's why there's hope that this is going to work.

386
00:32:51,300 --> 00:32:55,300
The heart problem is putting the pieces back together. There's no free lunch.

387
00:32:55,300 --> 00:32:57,300
So that is the challenge in calculus.

388
00:32:57,300 --> 00:33:02,300
Now that you've solved the little problems, how does that tell you about the original big problem?

389
00:33:02,300 --> 00:33:07,300
Well, all right, so we have names for those two parts, the easy and the hard part.

390
00:33:07,300 --> 00:33:11,300
The slicing part is what we call differential calculus, and that's actually easy.

391
00:33:11,300 --> 00:33:14,300
We usually teach that at the beginning of the semester.

392
00:33:15,300 --> 00:33:19,300
The hard part is the putting them back together, integrating everything into a whole,

393
00:33:19,300 --> 00:33:24,300
and that's integral calculus, the rebuilding part.

394
00:33:24,300 --> 00:33:26,300
All right, so that's our strategy.

395
00:33:26,300 --> 00:33:33,300
And so from that point of view, calculus is about this exploitation of the infinity principle.

396
00:33:33,300 --> 00:33:37,300
Now, you'll notice in the way I described what the principle is,

397
00:33:37,300 --> 00:33:39,300
that you're going to keep cutting and cutting indefinitely,

398
00:33:39,300 --> 00:33:46,300
you have to recognize that that's a wild fantasy that you could ever do that in real life.

399
00:33:46,300 --> 00:33:53,300
And it has to do with a fantasy that stuff of all kinds is what I'm going to call continuous.

400
00:33:53,300 --> 00:33:58,300
All right, so the infinity principle works nicely for things that are continuous,

401
00:33:58,300 --> 00:34:02,300
to anything that can be sliced finer and finer forever, endlessly.

402
00:34:02,300 --> 00:34:05,300
Those are what I'm going to call continuous, things that hold together,

403
00:34:05,300 --> 00:34:09,300
I mean, from two Latin words that mean holding together.

404
00:34:09,300 --> 00:34:11,300
No smallest parts.

405
00:34:11,300 --> 00:34:15,300
And I want to make sure you understand, since this is a talk about stories,

406
00:34:15,300 --> 00:34:20,300
that in math we tell ourselves stories just like everybody tells themselves stories.

407
00:34:20,300 --> 00:34:24,300
There is an enormous creative fantasy happening right now.

408
00:34:24,300 --> 00:34:29,300
The idea that matter is continuous, we know to be false, right?

409
00:34:29,300 --> 00:34:31,300
We believe in atoms.

410
00:34:31,300 --> 00:34:33,300
The word atom means uncuttable.

411
00:34:33,300 --> 00:34:35,300
There are smallest bits.

412
00:34:35,300 --> 00:34:38,300
You might not believe that atoms are the smallest bits,

413
00:34:38,300 --> 00:34:42,300
but we don't really talk about splitting an electron.

414
00:34:42,300 --> 00:34:46,300
We think at some level, matter can't be split farther.

415
00:34:46,300 --> 00:34:49,300
At least that's what the modern physicists tell us.

416
00:34:49,300 --> 00:34:54,300
And not just substance, but even time and space themselves.

417
00:34:54,300 --> 00:34:57,300
